                <head>253. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On May 27, 1988, President <persName corresp="#p_RRW_1">Ronald Reagan</persName>
                    signed National Security Decision Directive 307, “Review of United States Arms
                    Reduction Positions in Preparation for the Moscow Summit.” The <gloss
                        target="#t_NSDD_1">NSDD</gloss> set the following <gloss target="#t_US_1"
                        >U.S.</gloss> goals for the Strategic Arms Reduction Talks for the May
                    29–June 2 summit: “We will continue to advocate a legally binding sublimit of
                    3300 <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">ICBM</gloss> RVs and will discuss how to record
                    the current Soviet intentions with regard to their program”; “We will provide
                    the Soviets details of our proposed verification scheme for mobile ICBMs based
                    upon the decisions reflected in guidance issued on my behalf by the National
                    Security Council staff on May 24, 1988. <pb facs="0941" n="910" xml:id="pg_910"
                    /> Based on Soviet receptiveness to this verification approach, I will make the
                    decision in Moscow whether to discuss specific numerical limits on mobile ICBMs
                    and, if so, what limits to propose”; “If warranted by Soviet movement in other
                    areas, I am prepared to agree to allow testing and modernization of silo-based
                    heavy ICBMs subject to appropriate restrictions on the modernization of such
                    missiles (but <hi rend="italic">not</hi> on other <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1"
                        >ICBM</gloss> modernization) and subject to the United States having an
                    equal right to heavy ICBMs.” (Reagan Library, Executive Secretariat, <gloss
                        target="#t_NSC_1">NSC</gloss> National Security Decision Directives (<gloss
                        target="#t_NSDD_1">NSDD</gloss>), <gloss target="#t_NSDD_1">NSDD</gloss>
                    250) The guidance of May 24 was not found.</p>
                <p>In a section on Soviet Anti-Ballistic Missile (<gloss target="#t_ABM_1"
                        >ABM</gloss>) Treaty Non-Compliance and the <gloss target="#t_ABM_1"
                        >ABM</gloss> Treaty Review, the <gloss target="#t_NSDD_1">NSDD</gloss>
                    stated that <gloss target="#t_US_1">U.S.</gloss> officials would reaffirm their
                    “long-standing concern with Soviet failure to comply with and to correct Soviet
                    violations of the <gloss target="#t_ABM_1">ABM</gloss> Treaty” and “make it
                    clear that we will not sign any strategic arms agreements, either in <gloss
                        target="#t_START_1">START</gloss> or in Defense and Space, while the issue
                    of the illegal Soviet Krasnoyarsk radar remains unresolved, and that we consider
                    the only appropriate resolution to be dismantlement or destruction of the
                    radar.” (Ibid.)</p>
                <p>President <persName corresp="#p_RRW_1">Reagan</persName> arrived in Moscow on May
                    29 and delivered remarks alongside Soviet General Secretary <persName
                        corresp="#p_GM_1">Mikhail Gorbachev</persName> at the opening ceremony of
                    the summit. (“Remarks at the Opening Ceremony of the Soviet-United States Summit
                    Meeting in Moscow,” May 29, 1988; <hi rend="italic">Public Papers: <persName
                            corresp="#p_RRW_1">Reagan</persName>
                    </hi>, <hi rend="italic">1988</hi>, Book I, pages 672–674) In a one-on-one
                    meeting that afternoon in St. Catherine’s Hall of the Kremlin, <persName
                        corresp="#p_RRW_1">Reagan</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_GM_1"
                        >Gorbachev</persName> discussed previous meetings, human rights, and
                    religion. (Memorandum of Conversation, May 29; Department of State, Executive
                    Secretariat, <gloss target="#t_SS_1">S/S</gloss> Records, Memoranda of
                    Conversations Pertaining to United States and <gloss target="#t_USSR_1"
                        >USSR</gloss> Relations, 1981–1990, Lot 93D188, Moscow Summit 5/29–6/1,
                    1988) The memorandum of conversation is printed in <ref
                        target="frus1981-88v06#d156">
                        <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1981–1988, volume VI, Soviet
                        Union, October 1986–January 1989, Document 156</ref>.</p>
            </div>
